      <!-- Section 1: What llms.txt Is -->
      <section id="what-is-llms-txt" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>What llms.txt Is</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>An llms.txt file is a plain-text document, formatted in Markdown, that a website owner places at the root of their domain to give large language models and AI crawlers a structured, curated summary of the site's identity, purpose, and most important content.</strong>
          It was proposed by Jeremy Howard in September 2024 and is published as a community specification at llmstxt.org.
        </p>

        <p>
          The motivation for llms.txt comes from a practical problem: modern websites are complex. They contain hundreds or thousands of pages, many of which are navigational, administrative, or otherwise low-value for an AI system trying to understand what an organisation does and what it is authoritative about. A sitemap.xml tells crawlers where all the pages are. An llms.txt file tells AI systems which pages actually matter — and why.
        </p>

        <p>
          Think of llms.txt as the brief that you would hand to a journalist before an interview. It is the curated, accurate, self-authored description of who you are and what you are best placed to speak to. Without it, an AI system attempting to understand your brand has to infer your identity from whatever pages it happens to crawl — which may include outdated content, thin pages, or navigational templates that say nothing meaningful about your expertise.
        </p>

        <p>
          The file is served as plain text at <code>https://yourdomain.com/llms.txt</code>. For static site generators including Astro, it lives in the <code>public/</code> directory. It should be openly accessible — not blocked by robots.txt, not behind authentication, and not redirecting to another URL. AI crawlers that support the specification will request this file directly before or alongside crawling the rest of your site.
        </p>

        <p>
          This page is one of a set of technical GEO guides within our <a href="/ai-brand-visibility/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">AI brand visibility</a> NODE. For the broader strategic context — why AI crawlers matter and how they interact with citation — see the full <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">generative engine optimisation guide</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: Why It Matters for GEO -->
      <section id="why-it-matters" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Why llms.txt Matters for GEO</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>llms.txt is not a magic ranking signal — it is a clarity signal that reduces the probability of AI systems misrepresenting or ignoring your content.</strong>
          Its value is proportional to the quality of your underlying content and entity authority; deployed on a thin site with poor entity signals, it contributes little. Deployed on a well-structured site with strong schema markup and entity authority, it is a meaningful additional layer of AI-readability.
        </p>

        <p>
          The file serves three specific functions within a GEO programme:
        </p>

        <div class="not-prose mt-6 grid gap-5 sm:grid-cols-3">
          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--accent)] mb-2">Content Curation Signal</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              It tells AI crawlers which pages represent your most authoritative content — reducing the chance that a crawler indexes your cookie policy and ignores your pillar content.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--accent)] mb-2">Entity Clarification</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              The blockquote summary and service descriptions give AI systems a canonical, self-authored description of your organisation — supplementing schema markup and knowledge graph data.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-5">
            <h3 class="font-display text-sm font-semibold text-[var(--accent)] mb-2">Retrieval Efficiency</h3>
            <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              For RAG-based systems like Perplexity, an llms.txt file can reduce retrieval costs and latency by providing an index of high-value pages rather than requiring the system to crawl and rank all pages independently.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="mt-8">
          The deployment of llms.txt on this site is part of the broader GEO technical stack that also includes <a href="/schema-markup-ai/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">schema markup for AI</a>, structured content patterns, and entity authority building. For the service-level implementation, see our <a href="/geo-services/#llms-txt" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO services page</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: The Spec and Format -->
      <section id="spec-format" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>The llms.txt Specification and Format</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The llms.txt specification defines a Markdown-based file format with five required or recommended structural elements, each serving a distinct function for AI parsing.</strong>
          The format is intentionally simple — it uses standard Markdown with no custom syntax or proprietary extensions, which means it can be written in any text editor and read by any system capable of processing plain text.
        </p>

        <p>The five structural elements are:</p>

        <div class="not-prose mt-6 space-y-3">
          <div class="card p-5">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm text-[var(--accent)] font-bold">H1</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-ink-50">Brand / Organisation Name</h3>
                <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-ink-300">A single H1 containing your brand name. This is the top-level entity identifier — it should match the name in your Organisation schema and all external knowledge base entries. Do not add a tagline or description here.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-5">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm text-[var(--accent)] font-bold">&gt;</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-ink-50">Blockquote Summary</h3>
                <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-ink-300">A Markdown blockquote (prefixed with <code class="text-xs bg-geo-800 px-1 py-0.5 rounded">&gt;</code>) containing one to two sentences that describe your organisation and its primary function. This is the most-cited element of the file — AI systems use it to classify your brand when generating responses to category queries. Write it as a clear, factual definition, not a marketing strapline.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-5">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm text-[var(--accent)] font-bold">H2+</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-ink-50">Service and Expertise Sections</h3>
                <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-ink-300">H2-headed sections covering what you do, your areas of expertise, and your core services. Use bullet lists within each section. These sections help AI systems understand your topical authority and match your brand to relevant query categories.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-5">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm text-[var(--accent)] font-bold">URLs</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-ink-50">Key Pages with Annotations</h3>
                <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-ink-300">Bullet lists of your most important pages, each formatted as a Markdown link followed by an em dash and a plain-English description. Include only your most authoritative pages — 10 to 30 URLs is typical. Do not include every page on the site. Annotations should describe what each page covers, not market it.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-5">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="shrink-0 font-mono text-sm text-[var(--accent)] font-bold">...</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-ink-50">Optional: llms-full.txt Reference</h3>
                <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-ink-300">The spec allows an optional reference to an <code class="text-xs bg-geo-800 px-1 py-0.5 rounded">llms-full.txt</code> file containing a more comprehensive index of all pages. This is useful for large sites where the primary llms.txt focuses on pillar content. For most sites under 200 pages, a single well-structured llms.txt is sufficient.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4: Full Example File -->
      <section id="example" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Full Example llms.txt File</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>The example below is a realistic, well-structured llms.txt for a specialist GEO and AEO agency.</strong>
