        </div>

        <p class="mt-6">
          Several things to note about this example. The blockquote summary is factual and specific — it names the platforms, identifies the geography, and uses the correct full-form terminology on first use. The service list uses consistent parallel structure. The URL list is selective, not exhaustive — it covers pillar content, key guides, and commercial pages, not every URL on the site. The contact section is included because AI systems use it when generating responses that reference how to reach an organisation.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5: What to Include -->
      <section id="what-to-include" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>What to Include — and What to Leave Out</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>The most common mistake in llms.txt implementation is including too many URLs and too little context.</strong>
            A file listing 200 pages with no descriptions is less useful to an AI system than a file listing 20 pages with clear, factual annotations. Quality and selectivity are more important than comprehensiveness.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-geo-700">
          <table class="min-w-full text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-geo-700 bg-geo-900">
                <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-ink-50">Include</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-ink-50">Leave Out</th>
                <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-ink-50">Reason</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-geo-800">
              <tr class="bg-geo-950/60">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200">Pillar / ROOT pages</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Pagination pages</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Pillar pages represent your deepest authority; paginated pages have no standalone value for AI systems.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200">Key guide and NODE pages</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Tag and category archives</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Guides are citable; archives are navigational structure with no substantive content for citation.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="bg-geo-950/60">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200">Commercial service pages</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Privacy policy, T&amp;Cs, cookie pages</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Service pages define your offering; legal pages contain no citation-relevant expertise.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200">About and contact pages</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Checkout and login pages</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">About/contact provide entity context; transactional pages are useless for AI citation purposes.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="bg-geo-950/60">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200">Pages with unique data or research</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Thin SEED pages with low word count</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Unique data is highly citable; thin pages will be retrieved and found wanting, reducing overall trust.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-200">Pages with strong schema markup</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Pages without schema or structured data</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">Schema-rich pages parse cleanly and cite accurately; unstructured pages are harder for AI systems to use reliably.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
          <p>
            The annotation format matters as much as the page selection. Each annotation should answer the question: "What would someone learn from this page?" Not "What is this page about?" (that is what the URL says), but what specific knowledge, methodology, or data does it contain that is worth citing. "Complete GEO guide" is a stronger annotation than "about generative engine optimisation" because it signals depth and completeness — attributes that AI systems weight when selecting sources for complex queries.
          </p>
