      <!-- Section 7: llms.txt and robots.txt -->
      <section id="robots-txt" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>llms.txt and robots.txt: The Dependency You Cannot Ignore</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>An llms.txt file is completely ineffective if your robots.txt blocks the AI crawlers it is designed to help.</strong>
          This is the most critical dependency in AI crawler optimisation: crawler access permissions come before content signals, always. A crawler that is blocked by robots.txt will never read your llms.txt file — and will never retrieve or cite any of your pages, regardless of how excellent your structured data and content quality are.
        </p>

        <p>
          Common AI bot identifiers that are frequently blocked in robots.txt include:
        </p>

        <div class="not-prose">
          <pre class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg bg-geo-900 border border-geo-700 p-5 text-sm leading-relaxed"><code class="font-mono text-ink-200">{`# Crawlers that are commonly blocked — review and unblock as appropriate

User-agent: GPTBot          # OpenAI / ChatGPT
User-agent: ClaudeBot       # Anthropic / Claude
User-agent: PerplexityBot   # Perplexity
User-agent: Google-Extended # Google AI training and AI Overviews
User-agent: CCBot           # Common Crawl (feeds many model training sets)
User-agent: anthropic-ai    # Anthropic secondary crawler
User-agent: Applebot-Extended # Apple AI features`}</code></pre>
        </div>

        <p class="mt-6">
          If any of these appear in your robots.txt with a <code>Disallow: /</code> rule, that crawler cannot access your site. Before deploying or updating an llms.txt file, audit your robots.txt and confirm that the crawlers you want to permit have either an explicit <code>Allow: /</code> rule or are simply absent from the file (which defaults to full access).
        </p>

        <p>
          The correct configuration for a site that wants maximum AI visibility is a robots.txt that either does not mention AI bot user-agents at all (allowing all bots by default) or explicitly allows each named AI crawler. The llms.txt file then provides those permitted crawlers with a curated guide to your most important content.
        </p>

        <p>
          For guidance on entity optimisation that complements both your schema markup and llms.txt deployment, see our pages on <a href="/entity-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">entity optimisation</a> and <a href="/knowledge-graph-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">knowledge graph optimisation</a>. For the full technical implementation service, see the <a href="/geo-services/#llms-txt" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">llms.txt section of our GEO services</a>.
        </p>
      </section>

